Scope of the Reference Implementation

This release includes:

chat message fragments
structural meaning resolution logic
override / retraction / confirmation handling
demo applications (Python + HTML)
outputs and reference outputs
validation traces

ORL-Chat defines a deterministic communication model where meaning emerges from structure:

resolve(structure) ->

RESOLVED     if structurally consistent final meaning exists
INCOMPLETE   if required semantic elements are missing
ABSTAIN      if structure is conflicting or unsafe


What This Demonstrates

meaning reconstruction from fragmented messages
independence from message ordering
independence from timestamps and synchronized clocks
override and correction handling without ambiguity
safe handling of incomplete conversational states
conflict containment without corruption of meaning
deterministic convergence across independent nodes
reproducible conversational outcomes


Conformance

An implementation is considered compatible if it preserves:

structure-based meaning resolution
independence from order as authority
independence from synchronized time
deterministic convergence
reproducibility under equivalent inputs
explicit INCOMPLETE and ABSTAIN handling

Conformance is judged by observable behavior, not internal implementation.


Relationship to Shunyaya Framework

ORL-Chat is part of the broader Shunyaya Structural Universal Mathematics (SSUM) framework.

It builds on:

STOCRS — structure-first computation
SSUM-Time — time independence
ORL — structural ledger truth


